  "slug": "osso-buco",
  "title": "Osso buco",
  "subtitle": "Milanese braised shin, slow-cooked with wine, stock and gremolata.",
  "excerpt": "Cross-cut bone-in beef shin braised in white wine, stock and vegetables until the meat falls from the bone and the marrow slides from the cavity. Finished with gremolata. Traditionally served with risotto alla milanese. Serves four.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Osso buco alla milanese. The dish is documented in Ada Boni's Il Talismano della Felicità (1929) and in numerous mid-20th-century Italian cookbooks. Traditionally made with veal shin; beef shin is used here as a widely available substitute with comparable technique.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Osso buco means 'bone with a hole', the cross-cut shin with its central marrow cavity. The marrow melts during the braise and enriches the sauce; eating it from the bone with a small spoon is part of the ritual. The gremolata served at the end is not decoration: the fresh lemon zest and garlic cut through the richness in a way that transforms the dish.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Ask a butcher to cut the shin into 4 cm cross-sections. Tie each piece with kitchen twine to stop the meat falling away from the bone during the long braise.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
