      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Flour and brown the shin",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Pat {{beef-shin}} shin pieces dry with kitchen paper. Season with {{sea-salt-fine}} of salt and {{black-pepper}} of pepper, then dust lightly with {{plain-flour}} of flour. Heat {{olive-oil}} of olive oil in a large casserole over medium-high heat. Brown the shin pieces for 3 to 4 minutes per side until deeply golden. Work in batches; don't crowd the pan. Transfer to a plate.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Build the braise",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Reduce the heat to medium. In the same pan, cook {{onion}} diced onion, {{celery}} diced celery and {{carrot}} diced carrot for 10 minutes until soft. Add {{garlic}} of sliced garlic; cook for 2 minutes. Pour in {{white-wine-dry}} of white wine and let it reduce by half. Add {{tinned-tomatoes}} of tomatoes, {{stock-chicken}} of stock, {{thyme}} of thyme and {{bay-leaves}} of bay leaves. Return the shin pieces to the pot. The liquid should come about halfway up the meat.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Braise and finish",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Cover and cook on the lowest possible heat for 1.5 to 2 hours, turning the meat once, until it is very tender and beginning to part from the bone. Mix the gremolata: combine lemon zest, finely grated garlic and chopped parsley. Scatter over the dish at the table or stir in just before serving. Remove the twine and bay leaves.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Troubleshooting",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "intro": null,
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Make sure twine is secure before browning. Thinner pieces cook faster but fall apart; use 4 cm minimum.",
              "cause": "Twine not tied tightly enough, or pieces not thick enough.",
              "symptom": "Meat falling off the bone before it's cooked"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Remove the lid for the last 20 minutes to let the sauce reduce. Alternatively, remove the meat, boil the sauce down, and return.",
              "cause": "Too much liquid, or lid not slightly ajar.",
              "symptom": "Sauce too thin"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Add gremolata at the very end or at the table. A little goes a long way; start with half and taste.",
              "cause": "Too much raw garlic, or added too early.",
              "symptom": "Gremolata overpowering"
            }
          ],
          "heading": "Common problems"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Osso buco belongs to the serious winter table in Milan. It is traditionally served with saffron risotto, the two dishes completing each other: the rich, gelatinous braise alongside the golden, creamy rice. The marrow, eaten from the bone cavity with a small spoon, is considered the cook's reward.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
